snippet.textDisplay:
A physiotherapist who deals with lung disorders and is a specialist in respiration passed some information on to me which is not yet in the public domain.

The virus is causing a build-up of phlegm on the lungs which is a lot thicker than usual. If you are infected and just laying in bed, the phlegm is solidifying, once that happens, it can't be removed.

1: If you are coughing up green or yellow phlegm, your body is fighting the infection.

2: If the phlegm is a dark grey colour, your body is losing the fight and you have pneumonia, call 999

3: If you are infected, huffing (the medical terminology) is effective at clearing your lungs. Take a deep breath and exhale as quick as you can, imagine a smudge on glass or a mirror and exhale as if you are trying to steam up a mirror, do it with as much power as you can muster. it helps with lifting the phlegm from your lungs. do this repeatedly all through the day, maybe 2 or 3 times an hour.

4: The old tried and tested method of a bowl of steaming hot water with some Vicks is effective too, put your head over the bowl, use a towel to cover your head, do this 5 times a day (or more if you feel it necessary).

5: DO NOT USE COUGH SYRUP, if you're coughing, you don't want to suppress the cough on this one as you need to be coughing phlegm up.

6: It may be difficult, but...it's important to not be laid in one position for too long, this is causing phlegm to pool in your lungs. If you are infected catnap throughout the day and night, don't seep all the way through. It's important to keep as mobile as you possibly can.

PLEASE PASS THIS INFORMATION ON TO AS MANY PEOPLE AS YOU CAN, IT MAY SAVE LIVES.

snippet.textDisplay: Maybe the main reason it's spreading in the U.S. is because our experts keep telling us to not wear masks in public! Think that might have something to do with it? Maybe Hong Kong, Taiwan, and Singapore have so relatively few cases because they...wait for it.. ALL wear masks when out in public! Is it rocket science? Seems to be over the head of our "experts". "But we'd deplete the supplies of healthcare!" Then don't wear masks that healthcare uses. Make your own. Use a dust mask, a pollen mask, a homemade mask, a bandana. Anything to hinder the expulsion of droplets whenever you talk, sneeze, or cough. Again, it isn't rocket science. But our experts seem to be moving us toward economic ruin in their approach. Those Asian countries above aren't shutting their economies down, and yet their case load remains relatively low even though they are among the most densely populated places on earth. Look at any photo of people on the streets there, what do you see? Universal mask wearing, that's what. Go into any crowded grocery store or Walmart here. What do you see? Only a smattering of brave souls wearing masks. Why? Because most people are trusting their medical experts and authorities and dutifully refraining from wearing masks. Wake up people. The experts aren't always right.
